Breast Cancer Prediction¶

0. Background¶

Breast cancer is the most common cancer among women and the second leading cause of cancer death. Early diagnosis of cancer is critical. The sample obtained by an invasive technique can be easily digitized and used for computationally based diagnostic. Using machine learning methods for diagnostic can significantly increase processing speed and on a big scale can make the diagnostic significantly cheaper.

In this data challenge, we analyze the Breast Cancer Wisconsin (Original) dataset from UCI Machine Learning Repository. Features in this dataset were computed from a digitized image of a fine needle aspirate (FNA) of a breast mass. They describe characteristics of the cell nuclei present in the image. Several nuclei in each sample were analyzed. The dataset contains 699 observations and 9 attributes, and some missing values.

## Define linear correlation matrix
# http://www.statisticssolutions.com/correlation-pearson-kendall-spearman/
def plot_correlation_matrix(data, target_name=None,
                            labels=None, **kwds):
    """
    To calculate pairwise correlation between features.
    Extra arguments are passed on to DataFrame.corr()
    """

    if (data[target_name[0]] == 4).all(axis=0):
        label = labels[0]
        data = data.drop(labels=target_name, axis=1, inplace=False)
    elif (data[target_name[0]] == 2).all(axis=0):
        label = lables[1]
        data = data.drop(labels=target_name, axis=1, inplace=False)
    else:
        label = "all"

    # Add colorbar, make sure to specify tick locations to match desired ticklabels
    labels = data.corr(**kwds).columns.values

    fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(ncols=1, figsize=(8, 7))
    ax1.set_title("Correlations: " + label)

    args = {"annot": True, "ax": ax1, "vmin": 0, "vmax": 1, "annot_kws": {"size": 8},
            "cmap": plt.get_cmap("Blues", 20)}

    # Correlations are calculated with .corr() method
    sns.heatmap(data.corr(method="spearman"), **args)

    for ax in (ax1,):
        # shift location of ticks to center of the bins
        ax.set_xticks(np.arange(len(labels))+0.5, minor=False)
        ax.set_yticks(np.arange(len(labels))+0.5, minor=False)

        ax.set_xticklabels(labels, minor=False, ha="right", rotation=70)
        ax.set_yticklabels(labels, minor=False)

    plt.yticks(rotation=0)
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)

    plt.tight_layout()

    return display(plt.show())

Model Evaluation¶

Let's start by looking at some metrics to see if our classifier performed well at all.

In [33]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, f1_score, precision_score, recall_score, classification_report

def get_metrics(y_test, y_predicted):  
    # true positives / (true positives+false positives)
    precision = precision_score(y_test, y_predicted, pos_label=None,
                                    average='weighted')             
    # true positives / (true positives + false negatives)
    recall = recall_score(y_test, y_predicted, pos_label=None,
                              average='weighted')
    
    # harmonic mean of precision and recall
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_predicted, pos_label=None, average='weighted')
    
    # true positives + true negatives/ total
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_predicted)
    return accuracy, precision, recall, f1

def plot_precision_recall_vs_threshold(precisions, recalls, thresholds):
    """
    Modified from:
    Hands-On Machine learning with Scikit-Learn
    and TensorFlow; p.89
    """
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
    plt.title("Precision and Recall Scores as a function of the decision threshold")
    plt.plot(thresholds, precisions[:-1], "b--", label="Precision")
    plt.plot(thresholds, recalls[:-1], "g-", label="Recall")
    plt.ylabel("Score")
    plt.xlabel("Decision Threshold")
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    
plot_precision_recall_vs_threshold(p, r, thresholds)

Inspection¶

In order to make an actionnable decision, we need to actually inspect the kind of mistakes our classifier is making. Let's start by looking at the confusion matrix.

In [40]:
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

def plot_confusion_martix(y_test, y_predicted):
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_predicted)
    cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis] # normalize
    cm = np.round(cm, 2)

    tag_list = ['Benign', 'Malignant']
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = tag_list, columns = tag_list)

    plt.figure(figsize = (5,4))
    sns.set(font_scale=1.5) #for label size
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=True, cmap="YlGnBu", fmt='g')

    plt.title('Confusion Matrix\n')
    plt.xlabel('\nPredicted Label')
    plt.ylabel('True Label\n')
In [41]:
plot_confusion_martix(y_test, y_predicted_rf)

Our classifier creates more false positives (true benign but predicted malignant) than false negatives (true maligant but predicted benign)(proportionally). Depending on the use case, this seems desirable, since a flase negative is quite undesirable for a patient. If a normal cell was diaganosted as malignant, we can further ask the doctor to reevaluate this case. But we really don't want a malignant case to be undiaganosted.

In [42]:
def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, classes,
                          normalize=False,
                          title='Confusion matrix',
                          cmap=plt.cm.Blues):
    """
    This function prints and plots the confusion matrix.
    Normalization can be applied by setting `normalize=True`.
    """
    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
        print("Normalized confusion matrix")
    else:
        print('Confusion matrix, without normalization')

    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=45)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)

    fmt = '.2f' if normalize else 'd'
    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, format(cm[i, j], fmt),
                 horizontalalignment="center",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

ROC curve on various algorithms¶

In [50]:
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, auc
import time

def plot_roc_curves(classifiers, X, y):
    """Produce ROC curves for models given feature set X and labels y
    """
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=.2, random_state=41)
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
    for classifier in classifiers:
        print('Working on '+classifier+' classifier...')
        startclass=time.time()
        clf_train=classifiers[classifier].fit(X_train, y_train)
        #pickle.dump(clf_train,open(os.getcwd()+'/classifiers/'+classifier+'.classifier','wb'))
        y_score = clf_train.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

        fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_score)
        roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)

        plt.plot(fpr, tpr, lw=2, label='%s (area = %0.2f)' % (classifier, roc_auc))
        print(classifier+' classifier took '+str(time.time()-startclass)+' seconds.')
    #plt.axis('equal')
    plt.tick_params(labelsize=20)
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=2, linestyle='--')
    plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate',fontsize = 20)
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate',fontsize = 20)
    plt.title('Receiver operating characteristic')
    plt.legend(loc="lower right",fontsize = 20)
    plt.axis('equal')
    #plt.savefig(os.getcwd()+'/graphs/ROC_curves', format='png')

4. Conclusion¶

In this data challenge, I took a deep look into the data and built two models to predict whether a biopsied breast cell is benign (not harmful) or malignant (cancerous), given a set of attributes about the cell.

I compared Random Forest and Logistic Regression model. Both models have very similar metrics, with precision at 0.97 and recall at 0.97. The top 3 most important features are Uniformity of Cell Size, Bare Nuclei, and Bland Chromatin.

Further work will be using cross-validation to fine tune the hyperparameters for our model. And other models like SVM and ANN can also be tried to see if we can improve the prediction. The final goal is to minimize the false negatives.

5. More Analysis¶

5.1 What lead false negative?¶

It's worthwhile to see if there are any unifying properties of the false negatives. While 2% is by all means, low, this will still affect about 5 people.

check wrong predictions (false negative one), then check original (not scaled) feature. analyze features in these small set.

So conclusion, in our false negatives - patients who have cancer which go undiagnosed - clump thickness is rather large, as is marginal adhesion. These features can be looked for by doctors who want to follow up.

5.x Class imbalance (not important)¶

When we train a classifier we'll have to resample accordingly.

There are two common choices when dealing with imbalanced data. One is upsampling; duplicating or artificially generating more points from your minority class. For us that means generating more malignant tumors. The other is downlsampling; deleting or ignoring points from your majority class.

see Adam's code

5.x Duplicate rows¶

  • Brain OGorman

So some there are some entire rows that are duplicates, but also some where just the sample_id is duplicated.

It is unclear why we might have some instances of just the ID being duplicated and other instances where the entire rows are. There is an additional data file from the original source (https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/breast-cancer-wisconsin/breast-cancer-wisconsin.names) that provides some additional information. After spot-checking a handful of these duplicates, it appears that cases where the entire rows are duplicated were samples that were taken on the same date. Cases where only the sample_id is duplicated are from different dates. Based on this, I am going to drop the entries where the entire rows are duplicated, but not those where only the sample_id is.

This exploration of the breast cancer biopsy labels arose from the desire to provide a model to classify whether a biopsy sample was benign or malignant. After a quick exploration of the features a number of models were trained and seen to perform quite well (auc>0.9) on a test set of data reserved from the training. The number of false positives in the prediction were minimized by changing the classification threshold for the positive (malignant) and negative (benign) class. In this way the risk of miss identifying malignant tumours is minimized.

Next, I sought to improve upon the standard diagnostic procedures currently in place for biopsy classification. From my (limited) understanding, the features that are most revealing are the size and distribution of the nuclei. With this in mind, I hypothesized that the typical diagnostic tools could rely too heavily on these features and as such may skew a manual classification of the tumour. With that in mind I removed the features related to the appearance of the nuclei. The hope is that the model should be robust to the bias the human classification has and so if the highly correlated variables are removed it could better fit (or stop overfitting) to the highly predictive features. Repeating the analysis I found that the performance of the models (Gradient Boosting Classifier, Random Forest Classifier and Logistic Regression) did not change after removing the highly predictive features. This could be a route forward for clinicians to move away from qualitative indicators of malignant tumours to a more quantitative and automated diagnosis.

Some things to think about going forward:

I noticed that the performance was fairly robust against reevaluations of this notebook but the features and their importance varied a fair bit. To combat this I could bootstrap and bag the results to average the model over different training data. I could try using PCA or another tool for dimensionality reduction to infer "better" observables that could be used going forward in biopsy diagnostics. However, this could be a dead end as it may not be interpretable.
